istorical folds, emergent politics, and dissonant times—in turn, provided the conditions for the development of three previously unnamed genres of the 1850s: the Pacific elegy, the black counterfactual, and the immigrant gothic.In telling the history of these emergent worlds and their importance to the development of the literary cultures of the US Americas, Sugden proposes narratives that alter some of the most enduring myths of the field, including the westward spread of US imperialism, the redemptionist trajectory of black historiography, and the notion that the US Americas constituted a new world. Introducing a new generic vocabulary for describing the literature of the 1850s and crossing over oceans and languages, Emergent Worlds invokes an alternative nineteenth-century America that provides nothing less than a new way to read the era.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2021) 0aAmerican literaturey19th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aLiterature and historyzUnited States. 0aPolitical culturexHistoryy19th century. 0aSocial change in literature. 0aSocial changexHistoryy19th century. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / American / General.2bisacsh  aBenito Cereno.  aCaribbean.  aHaiti.  aHerman Melville.  aJames Fenimore Cooper.  aLiberia.  aPacific elegy.  aPacific.  aSierra Leone.  aarchival.  ablack counterfactual.  ablack historiography.  acity mysteries.  ademocracy.  adissonant times.  aemergent politics.  aemergent worlds.  agenres.  ageoculture.  ahistorical folds.  aimmigrant gothic.  aimmigration.  ainterstices.  ainterstitial.  amoby dick.  anativism.  anineteenth-century America.  aoceanic geography.  aoceanic.  aqueer migrant.  aslavery.  asuspended state.  asystemic uncertainty.  athreshold state.  atransition state.  aworld-system.08iTi